                     <interp inst="t18390513-1515-offence-1" type="offenceSubcategory" value="stealingFromMaster"></interp> for stealing, on the <rs id="t18390513-cd-42" type="crimeDate">
                        <join result="offenceCrimeDate" targOrder="Y" targets="t18390513-1515-offence-1 t18390513-cd-42"></join>12th of March</rs>, 1 bottle, value 1<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and half a pint of gin, value 8<hi rend="italic">d</hi>., and 2 half sovereigns, the goods and monies of <persName id="t18390513-name-295" type="victimName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-295" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-295" type="surname" value="GODLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-295" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>
                        <join result="offenceVictim" targOrder="Y" targets="t18390513-1515-offence-1 t18390513-name-295"></join>Charles Godland</persName>, his master.</rs>
               </p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390513-name-296" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-296" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-296" type="surname" value="GODLAND"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-296" type="given" value="CHARLES"></interp>CHARLES GODLAND</persName>
                  </hi>. I keep the Golden Anchor public-house in St. John-street, Clerkenwell—the prisoner was my pot-boy—he left me on the 12th of March without notice—I met him the same day between 11 and 12 o'clock, beyond Sadlers' Wells, going towards Islington, and when I got home, I heard what he had had—he never returned to me—I heard him</p>
               <xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="183905130034"></xptr>
               <p>say at Union Hall, that he had taken the gin to Margaret-street, and the parties had removed—I went and saw them in a court in Brook-street, Holborn—they said they never gave him an order to bring any gin—what they wanted they fetched.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390513-name-297" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-297" type="gender" value="female"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-297" type="surname" value="M'DONALD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-297" type="given" value="ELEANOR"></interp>ELEANOR M'DONALD</persName>
                  </hi>. I assist in the prosecutor's business—on the 12th of March the prisoner came to me for change for a sovereign and half a pint of gin—I turned to the mistress, and asked her for the change—she said she had no silver, but she handed me two half sovereigns—I gave the prisoner the two half sovereigns, and the half pint of gin, and saw no more of him.</p>
               <p>
                  <hi rend="smallCaps">
                     <persName id="t18390513-name-298" type="witnessName">
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-298" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-298" type="surname" value="HIGHWOOD"></interp>
                        <interp inst="t18390513-name-298" type="given" value="JOHN"></interp>JOHN HIGHWOOD</persName>
                  </hi> (<hi rend="italic">police-constable M</hi> 102.) I took the prisoner—he at first denied his name, but a person said, "Don't deny your name"—he then said it was his name—one of the people at the station-house knew him, and said to him, "What are you here for, Charley?"—he said, "I know what it is for; for change of a sovereign; the parties made me drunk at the house; I lost a half sovereign, and did not like to go home."</p>
